ng can serve not just as an illustration for philosophical arguments, but also as the model for them--that painting itself has sometimes been a form of epistemological experiment, and that, perhaps surprisingly, the Neapolitan Baroque may have been one of the routes through which modern consciousness was formed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArt and philosophyzItalyxHistoryy18th century. 0aArt and philosophy. 0aMalerei. 0aPaintingxPhilosophy. 0aPainting, BaroquezItalyxNaples. 0aPainting, BaroquezItalyzNaples. 0aPainting, Baroque. 0aPainting, ItalianzItalyxNaplesy18th century. 0aPainting, ItalianzItalyzNaplesy18th century. 0aPainting, Italian. 0aTruth. 0aÄsthetik. 7aART / European.2bisacsh  aAesthetics.  aAnalogy.  aAndrea Vaccaro.  aAndrea del Sarto.  aAnecdote.  aAnnibale Carracci.  aAnthropomorphism.  aAtheism.  aAtomism.  aAugury.  aBad Painting.  aBaroque painting.  aCaravaggio.  aCaravaggisti.  aCarlo Maratta.  aCartesianism.  aCatherine of Siena.  aCertainty.  aCertosa di San Martino.  aChiaroscuro.  aCimabue.  aClassical mythology.  aClassicism.  aConsciousness.  aCubism.  aDaniello Bartoli.  aDemocritus.  aDepiction.  aDivine Truth.  aDivine judgment.  aDivine providence.  aDomenichino.  aDrapery.  aEpicurus.  aExorcism.  aFall of Simon Magus (Pompeo Batoni).  aFalsity.  aFlagellation of Christ.  aFrancesco Solimena.  aGiambattista Vico.  aGiotto.  aGod the Father.  aGuido Reni.  aHenri Bergson.  aIconoclasm.  aIconography.  aIllustration.  aJules Michelet.  aLas Meninas.  aLibri Carolini.  aLodovico Dolce.  aLuca Giordano.  aLucretius.  aLudovico Carracci.  aMannerism.  aMetaphor.  aMetonymy.  aMichelangelo.  aMuseo del Prado.  aNeoplatonism.  aPainti